Subject: antero-dorsal region
Value: anterodorsal region

Subject: antero-ventral region
Value: anteroventral region

Subject: medial-lateral axis
Value: proximal-distal axis

Subject: synonym typically used in the context of human anatomy
synonym typically used in the context of vertebrate anatomy
deep-superficial gradient (obsolete)
Value: deep-superficial gradient (obsolete)

Subject: anatomical relation
Value: anatomical relation

Subject: anterior to
Value: x anterior to y iff x is further along the antero-posterior axis than y, towards the head. An antero-posterior axis is an axis that extends through an organism from head end to opposite end of body or tail.

Subject: distal to
Value: x distal to y iff x is further along the proximo-distal axis than y, towards the appendage tip. A proximo-distal axis extends from tip of an appendage (distal) to where it joins the body (proximal).

Subject: dorsal to
Value: x dorsal to y iff x is further along the dorso-ventral axis than y, towards the back. A dorso-ventral axis is an axis that extends through an organism from back (e.g. spinal column) to front (e.g. belly).

Subject: posterior to
Value: x posterior to y iff x is further along the antero-posterior axis than y, towards the body/tail. An antero-posterior axis is an axis that extends through an organism from head end to opposite end of body or tail.

Subject: proximal to
Value: x proximal to y iff x is closer to the point of attachment with the body than y.

Subject: ventral to
Value: x ventral to y iff x is further along the dorso-ventral axis than y, towards the front. A dorso-ventral axis is an axis that extends through an organism from back (e.g. spinal column) to front (e.g. belly).

Subject: in proximal side of
Value: x in proximal side of y <=> if y is subdivided into two proximal and distal portions, y is part of the proximal portion.

Subject: in distal side of
Value: x in distal side of y <=> if y is subdivided into two proximal and distal portions, y is part of the distal portion.

Subject: immediately deep to
Value: x immediately deep to y iff x deep_to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: postaxial to
Value: x preaxial to y iff x is further along the preaxial-postaxial axis than y, towards the postaxial side.

Subject: orthogonal to
Value: crossing at right angles

Subject: immediately anterior to
Value: x immediately anterior to y iff x anterior to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately distal to
Value: x immediately distal to y iff x distal to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately dorsal to
Value: x immediately dorsal to y iff x dorsal to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately posterior to
Value: x immediately posterior to y iff x posterior_to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately proximal to
Value: x immediately proximal to y iff x proximal to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately superficial to
Value: x immediately superficial to y iff x superficial to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately ventral to
Value: x immediately ventral to y iff x ventral to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately left of
Value: x immediately left of y iff x left_of y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately right of
Value: x immediately right of y iff x right of y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: oral to
Value: nearer to the oral opening of the organism, on the oral-aboral axis.

Subject: aboral to
Value: nearer to the aboral opening of the organism, on the oral-aboral axis.

Subject: preaxial to
Value: x preaxial to y iff x is further along the preaxial-postaxial axis than y, towards the front.

Subject: parallel to
Value: x is parallel t y iff x and y are lines or planes which when extended indefinitely do not cross.
